          "body": "Verses 16-20 apply the argument pastorally. Having established the principle (vv. 5-15), the psalmist now addresses the reader directly with a command: 'Do not be afraid when a man becomes rich, when the glory of his house is increased' (v. 16). The imperative is grounded on three facts. First, he carries nothing at death (v. 17) — not one piece of his accumulated *kavod* (glory) descends with him. Second, his self-congratulation and his admirers' praise are confined entirely to his lifetime (v. 18) — peer approval ends at the grave. Third, he joins the generation of his ancestors, who never see the light (v. 19) — the dynasty he imagined becomes a line of the lightless. The psalm closes with its second refrain (v. 20), nearly identical to v. 12 but with a critical addition: 'without understanding.' The first refrain condemned the wealthy for their pomp; the second condemns them for their *failure to understand*. The wisdom the psalmist offered in vv. 1-4 was precisely the understanding that they refused. The beast-like perishing is not simply imposed by fate; it is the consequence of choosing to trust wealth over the God who alone redeems."
