        "excerpt": "But God will redeem my soul from the power of Sheol, for He will receive me.",
        "body": "Verse 15 is the theological center of the entire psalm, marked by the Selah that follows it and the adversative *akh* ('but' / 'surely') that introduces it. Against the relentless impossibility of vv. 7-9 — no man can redeem his brother, the price is too costly, he should cease trying forever — the psalmist sets a single confident confession: 'But God will redeem my soul from the power of Sheol, for He will receive me.' The symmetry is deliberate. The same verb *padah* used for the human ransom that cannot be paid (vv. 7, 8) now describes what God will do (v. 15). The impossibility of the one magnifies the certainty of the other.\n\nVerse 14 prepares the contrast. The wealthy are appointed for Sheol 'like sheep' — *tson*, a flock animal, utterly subject to its shepherd's direction. Their shepherd is Death itself, personified in a grotesque inversion of Psalm 23: where the LORD is the shepherd who leads to green pastures, Death is the shepherd who leads to Sheol. The upright will 'rule over them in the morning' — *boqer*, a temporal marker for eschatological reversal after a night of apparent defeat (Psalm 30:5; Hosea 6:3). Whether this 'morning' describes a this-life vindication or a post-mortem one is a question the psalm does not resolve; it is content to assert the reversal without mapping its chronology.\n\nThe phrase 'He will receive me' (*laqach*, v. 15) carries enormous canonical weight. The verb is used of Enoch — 'God took him' (Genesis 5:24, the same root) — and of Elijah's translation (2 Kings 2:3, 5, 9, 10). Both are Old Testament figures whose deaths were superseded by God's direct act of reception. The psalmist does not claim to be exempt from dying; he claims that whatever Sheol does to his body, God will take him. The Reformers — Calvin especially (*Commentary on the Psalms*) — read this verse as one of the Old Testament's clearest anticipations of resurrection hope: not a fully developed doctrine, but a confident reach of faith beyond the grave grounded in the character of a God who has already demonstrated He can take people to Himself.\n\nThis verse is also the interpretive key to the entire psalm's pastoral argument. The reason the psalmist can say 'why should I fear?' (v. 5) is not that death is pleasant or that the wealthy are ultimately harmless — it is that his soul's destination is secured by an act of God that no oppressor can obstruct. Fear before the wealthy presupposes that wealth is the decisive currency. The psalmist has shown it is not.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Akh* (but / surely, v. 15) — a strong adversative or affirmative particle, marking the psalm's sharpest turn. *Padah* (redeem, v. 15) — kinsman-redeemer vocabulary, deliberate echo of vv. 7-8. *Laqach* (receive, take, v. 15) — Enoch-vocabulary (Genesis 5:24), Elijah-vocabulary (2 Kings 2:3). *Yad Sheol* (the power / hand of Sheol) — *yad* is 'hand' or 'power'; Sheol is personified as holding its captives in its grip, from which God extracts the psalmist."
