        "body": "The psalm's second panel (vv. 16-20) applies the argument of the first panel directly to the reader. Having demonstrated that wealth cannot ransom the soul (vv. 7-9), that death levels all human accumulation (vv. 10-12), and that God alone redeems (v. 15), the psalmist now issues the command the entire argument has been preparing: 'Do not be afraid' (*al-tira*, v. 16). This is not an exhortation to stoic detachment; it is a logical imperative grounded on evidence. If the foregoing argument is correct, then fear before the prosperous wicked is a category error — it treats wealth as the decisive power when death has already shown it to be temporary.\n\nThree specific grounds for fearlessness are given. First, 'when he dies he will carry nothing away; his glory will not descend after him' (v. 17). The word *kavod* (glory, splendor) is the same word used of God's own weight and majesty elsewhere in the Psalter — but here it is the wealthy man's earthly *kavod* that ends at the grave. Second, the self-congratulation of the prosperous (v. 18 — 'he congratulates himself') and the social approval of his peers ('men praise you when you do well for yourself') are exposed as empty currencies. Praise that is contingent on prosperity is not a reliable index of a life well-lived before God. Third, 'he shall go to the generation of his fathers; they will never see the light' (v. 19). The dynasty the wealthy man imagined — the houses built to last forever, the lands named after him — ends in the darkness of those who do not see the light of God's presence (cf. Psalm 36:9; Isaiah 9:2).\n\nThe closing refrain (v. 20) is nearly identical to v. 12 but with a critical intensification: 'Man in his pomp, yet **without understanding**, is like the beasts that perish.' The first refrain (v. 12) named the condition: man in his pomp does not endure. The second refrain names the cause: the man of wealth who lacks *bin* (understanding, discernment) — who has received the wisdom of this psalm and refused it — is the one whose beast-like perishing is self-chosen. The psalm offered understanding in its opening verses (v. 3); it closes by condemning those who, having heard, chose not to receive it. Wealth is not the condemned thing; wealth without understanding is. The man of means who holds his resources with open hands, trusts the God who redeems, and keeps the wisdom of v. 15 at the center of his confidence — he is not the target of this psalm's rebuke.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Al-tira* (do not be afraid, v. 16) — the same imperative form used in the great 'fear not' passages of Isaiah (41:10, 13, 14; 43:1). *Kavod* (glory, v. 17) — the word for God's own weighty presence repurposed for human accumulated splendor; the irony is pointed. *Bin* (understanding, v. 20) — the root of *binah*, the understanding listed as a gift of the Spirit in Isaiah 11:2 and the characteristic of wisdom in Proverbs 1:2. Its absence at the end of the psalm is the diagnosis of every generation that reads the riddle and walks away."
